<p>Every boat owner in South Devon has dealt with biofouling, even if they've never heard the word. It's the green slime on your waterline, the barnacles on your keel, the mysterious roughness you feel when you run your hand along the hull at low tide. But what actually is it, how does it get there, and why does it matter beyond aesthetics?</p>

<h2>The Science in Plain English</h2>

<p>Marine biofouling is the accumulation of organisms on submerged surfaces. That's the textbook definition. In practical terms, it's nature doing what nature does best — colonising every available surface in the ocean. Your hull is just another rock as far as marine biology is concerned, and organisms have evolved over millions of years to be extremely good at attaching to hard surfaces in water.</p>

<p>The process begins within minutes of a clean hull entering the water. A conditioning film of dissolved organic molecules — proteins, polysaccharides, glycoproteins — adsorbs onto the surface. You can't see this film. You can't feel it. But it fundamentally changes the surface chemistry of your hull, making it more hospitable for what comes next.</p>

<p>Within hours to days, bacteria arrive. These pioneers form what scientists call a biofilm — a structured community of microorganisms embedded in a self-produced matrix of extracellular polymeric substances. In less technical terms: slime. This bacterial biofilm is the foundation layer for everything that follows, and it's remarkably tenacious. Even at this early stage, your hull's hydrodynamic performance has already started to degrade.</p>

<h2>The Fouling Calendar</h2>

<p>In South Devon's temperate waters, fouling follows a broadly predictable seasonal pattern. Understanding this calendar helps you time your cleaning interventions for maximum effectiveness.</p>

<p><strong>Spring (March–May):</strong> As water temperatures climb above 8-10°C, biological activity accelerates rapidly. The bacterial biofilm that persisted over winter becomes a substrate for diatoms — single-celled photosynthetic organisms that form a brown or golden slime. This is the stage most boat owners first notice, particularly at the waterline. It's also the easiest and cheapest stage to clean.</p>

<p><strong>Summer (June–August):</strong> Peak fouling season. Barnacle larvae (cyprids) settle onto the biofilm and diatom layer, cementing themselves permanently with one of the strongest natural adhesives known to science. Green macroalgae colonises available surfaces. Tubeworms, bryozoans, and hydroids establish colonies. By mid-summer, a hull left untreated since spring can carry a diverse and well-established fouling community that significantly increases drag.</p>

<p><strong>Autumn (September–November):</strong> Growth rates slow as temperatures drop, but the organisms that established over summer persist. Barnacle shells harden and their adhesive bond strengthens. Algae dies back partially but leaves structural remnants that trap silt and sediment.</p>

<p><strong>Winter (December–February):</strong> Biological growth is minimal, but this is a deceptive quiet. The fouling community that survived autumn is now firmly established, and removing winter-hardened barnacles requires significantly more mechanical effort than removing them in their juvenile summer stages.</p>

<h2>What Fouling Actually Costs You</h2>

<p>The financial impact of biofouling operates on two fronts: direct performance costs and indirect maintenance costs.</p>

<p>On the performance side, the numbers are well-documented. Research from the University of Melbourne found that even a light biofilm (slime layer only, no macrofouling) can increase frictional resistance by 10-16%. For a sailing yacht, that means reduced speed through the water. For a motor vessel, it means burning more fuel to maintain the same speed. A 15-metre motor cruiser with moderate fouling can easily consume 15-20% more fuel than the same vessel with a clean hull — and at current diesel prices, that adds up to hundreds of pounds over a single season.</p>

<p>On the maintenance side, heavy fouling accelerates antifouling paint degradation. When barnacles are eventually removed — whether by cleaning or during a haul-out — they pull ablative antifouling layers away with them. This shortens the useful life of your antifouling coating, bringing forward the date of your next repaint. Given that a full antifouling application for a 12-metre yacht costs £800-1,500 in materials and labour, anything that extends the interval between repaints is worth taking seriously.</p>

<h2>Why Location Matters</h2>

<p>Not all harbours produce the same fouling. In Brixham, the commercial fishing fleet churns nutrients through the water, accelerating algae growth and creating conditions that barnacle larvae thrive in. In Dartmouth, the River Dart's estuarine conditions introduce freshwater, agricultural runoff, and fine sediment that create a unique fouling profile dominated by silt-embedded algae and brackish-water species. In Torquay, warmer English Riviera temperatures extend the active fouling season compared to harbours further north.</p>

<p>Understanding your location's specific fouling profile helps you choose the right cleaning frequency. A quarterly clean that works perfectly for a boat in a sheltered Torquay berth might be insufficient for a vessel on a Dartmouth swing mooring, where the combination of stationary exposure and nutrient-rich river water accelerates fouling significantly.</p>

<h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

<p>Biofouling isn't a cosmetic issue — it's a performance, maintenance, and financial issue. The organisms colonising your hull are costing you fuel, costing you antifouling life, and costing you the enjoyment of a responsive, clean-bottomed boat. The good news is that regular professional cleaning, timed to intervene before fouling hardens and bonds permanently, keeps these costs under control and extends the working life of your hull coating.</p>

